411 | One of the greatest things to happen to me in the past decade was meeting @brianabane at a job. One of the greatest things to happen last year, was when Bri became this podcast’s editor… 

This happened after visiting her one morning l when I was so stressed and overwhelmed. I told her what was going on with the podcast, and basically soon she was editing episodes… 

 Bri saved the podcast, but she’s more than merely a lifesaver… she makes me laugh harder than most people do and gives wise gentle advice, and you’ll hear her do both in this week’s episode. 

We tell how we met, fell in love, and both ended up moving from NY to LA and working together again and again…plus, it’s a mailbag episode so we answer questions submitted by listeners. They cover astrology, gift giving and receiving, our most midwestern qualities, and more.

I’m real glad we met, work a billion jobs together, and ended up on this coast. Let us know if you listen…

419 | “What You Run From Will Chase You” with Danielle LaPorte... (3/3)

⁠
Danielle LaPorte is an author and poet living in Vancouver, Canada. I’ve been reading her books for nearly a decade and this is her second time on the podcast. We spoke over zoom a few weeks ago about what she’s been learning lately, self-help exhaustion, how non-duality is a creative act, having the courage to make what she calls the 11th hour change, and how I discovered her in 2013 and her memory of day. She quotes Krishnamurti saying “discipline is a tool that numbs the mind,”our tendency to overwork, take on too many projects so we have to stay up late and eat crackers for dinner. We get into her thoughts on time, what she calls “tyrant time" vs "power time”, and how she believes you can bend time, and much more. Her new book is called “How to Be Loving” Let us know if you listen.⁠

my friend sat on a stranger’s stoop the day she moved to nyc. after a while, the stranger went inside for a box of soon-to-be donated books, gave them to my friend, and told her to read them all. ten years later, one by one my friend gave me books from that box. this was the first book and well, it was a hit… 
ie. all these phone photos of my tattered copy. you’ve likely seen me rereading it or I’ve given you a copy, or sent you a picture of a part… and if not, watch out… you could be next. 
thanks Kundera, Crystal, the stoop stranger
